I'm uploading a TIA/P25 standard document. Please process it through the following pipeline.

## Phase 1: Classification

Before any extraction, examine the document and classify it into one of these categories:

- **ALGORITHM** — Defines computational procedures: LFSRs, polynomials, FEC encoding, vocoder math, encryption protocols, modulation schemes. (Examples: BBAC scrambling, BBAB physical layer, AAAD encryption)
- **MESSAGE_FORMAT** — Defines wire-format message structures: opcodes, byte layouts, field definitions, PDU framing. (Examples: AABC trunking messages, AABF link control words, BAAC reserved values)
- **PROTOCOL** — Defines behavioral procedures and state machines: call setup sequences, registration flows, handoff logic. Often combined with MESSAGE_FORMAT. (Examples: BBAC MAC procedures, BACA ISSI)
- **VOCODER** — Defines audio codec parameters, frame structures, quantization tables. (Example: BABA half-rate vocoder)
- **MEASUREMENT** — Defines test methods, pass/fail thresholds, measurement configurations. No implementation code needed. (Examples: CAAA transceiver measurements, CCAA TDMA measurements)
- **CONFORMANCE** — Defines compliance test cases and profiles. No implementation code needed. (Examples: BCAD, BCAE, BCAF)
- **OVERVIEW** — Architecture documents, system descriptions, standards suite guides. (Example: TSB-102.BBAA)

State the classification and briefly explain why. A single document may span multiple categories (e.g., BBAC is both MESSAGE_FORMAT and PROTOCOL with ALGORITHM sections).

## Phase 2: Core Extraction (All Documents)

Produce these three files regardless of classification:

### File 1: Full Text Extraction (.md)
Extract all text in order from the document, including tables (as markdown tables) and descriptions of any images, charts, or diagrams. Skip the Notice page and the copyright page — I handle disclaimers separately in my app. For any mathematical formulas, equations, or expressions: reconstruct them into readable code-block notation, using surrounding prose to verify correct structure. Flag any formulas where the extraction was ambiguous. Save as `{DOC_NUMBER}_Full_Text.md`.

### File 2: ~1,000-Word Summary (.txt)
Write a ~1,000 word summary suitable for search results. Cover: what the document specifies, why it exists, what it defines or tests, key parameters and requirements, relationships to other documents in the suite, and any limitations it acknowledges. Save as `{DOC_NUMBER}_Summary.txt`.

### File 3: Related Resources & Context (.md)
Search the web for resources that reference this spec. Produce a .md file covering:
- **Status** — Active, expired, superseded, or absorbed? What replaced it?
- **Standards Family** — Where does it fit in the TIA-102 suite? List companion documents.
- **Practical Context** — How is this standard used in real-world equipment and systems?
- **Key Online Resources** — Relevant websites, archives, vendor pages (include URLs).
- **Open-Source Implementations** — Projects that implement what this document specifies (GitHub URLs).
- **Standards Lineage** — Document hierarchy as an ASCII tree.
Keep references neutral — use "this document" rather than the title. Do not include personal context about me. Save as `{DOC_NUMBER}_Context.md`.

## Phase 3: Implementation Specs (Classification-Dependent)

Based on the Phase 1 classification, produce additional implementation-focused files:

### For ALGORITHM documents:
Produce a standalone implementation spec (.md) for each significant algorithm. Include:
- Complete mathematical definitions with all constants as code-ready data (hex arrays, bit masks)
- Pseudocode for the full processing pipeline
- Any matrices, lookup tables, or generator polynomials as literal arrays
- Test vectors with worked examples
- Cross-validation references (SDRTrunk, OP25, or other open-source implementations)
- Language-agnostic but include Rust-specific notes where relevant

**CRITICAL: Extract matrices and large constant tables programmatically from the PDF** (PyMuPDF text extraction, then parse). Do NOT hand-transcribe — this session proved that manual transcription of 44x44 binary matrices introduces errors in ~30% of rows.

### For MESSAGE_FORMAT documents:
Produce a message parsing spec (.md) including:
- Complete opcode identification table (first-byte dispatch)
- Message length determination logic (fixed, variable, length-octet methods)
- Byte-level format diagrams for each message type
- Field definitions with bit positions and semantics
- Parser pseudocode showing the dispatch + extraction pattern
- Notes on abbreviated vs extended form selection rules
- Forward-compatibility skip logic for unknown messages

### For PROTOCOL documents:
Produce a state machine / procedures spec (.md) including:
- State diagrams or state tables for each procedure (call setup, maintenance, teardown, preemption)
- PDU sequencing requirements (which PDUs sent when, minimum counts, timing)
- Decision trees for subscriber and FNE behavior
- Error handling and timeout behavior
- SACCH/FACCH ultraframe scheduling rules if applicable

### For VOCODER documents:
Produce parameter extraction only (tables of quantization values, frame structure). Note that full vocoder implementation typically requires the JMBE/AMBE codec libraries.

### For MEASUREMENT / CONFORMANCE / OVERVIEW documents:
No implementation spec needed. Phase 2 extraction is sufficient.

## Processing Strategy

**Always prefer visual/context-window reading over programmatic text extraction.** When the PDF pages are visible in your context window as rasterized images, read them directly — this produces far superior results for bit-field diagrams, tables with cell spans, formulas with superscripts/subscripts, and vector-drawn figures.

**If the document exceeds ~150 pages, consider splitting it.** With a 1M token context window, documents up to ~120-150 pages can typically be processed in a single pass. Beyond that, split at **natural section boundaries** (use the table of contents) — never mid-section. Target 80-120 page chunks. When splitting, include 2-3 pages of overlap at each boundary so that figures/tables that follow their referencing text across a page break are not orphaned. If a split unavoidably lands between a text description and its figure/table on the next page, note this in the output and flag it for manual review. Save the split PDFs for download. Then start a new conversation for each chunk, uploading the chunk with this prompt and a note: "This is Part N of N — pages XX-YY covering [sections]."

**For programmatic extraction of tables and matrices:** Use PyMuPDF with color-based filtering to remove watermarks (TIA "Limited Use Only" watermarks are typically ~#bfbfbf at ~50pt, footer text ~#ababab at ~9pt). Still visually read pages with bit-field diagrams, formulas, or complex tables — stitch those into the programmatic output.

**For constant data (matrices, sync sequences, opcode tables):** Always extract programmatically and spot-check against rendered pages. Include the extraction method in the output file metadata.

## File Naming Convention

All output files should use this pattern:
```
{DOC_NUMBER}_Full_Text.md
{DOC_NUMBER}_Summary.txt  
{DOC_NUMBER}_Context.md
{DOC_NUMBER}_{Topic}_Implementation_Spec.md    (if applicable)
{DOC_NUMBER}_Annex_{X}_{Description}.md         (if large annexes extracted separately)
```

Examples:
```
TIA-102-BBAC-1_Full_Text.md
TIA-102-BBAC-1_Summary.txt
TIA-102-BBAC-1_Context.md
TIA-102-BBAC-1_Scrambling_Implementation_Spec.md
TIA-102-BBAC-1_MAC_Message_Parsing_Spec.md
TIA-102-BBAC-1_Annex_E_Burst_Bit_Tables.md
```

## Quality Checklist

Before delivering, verify:
- [ ] All formulas reconstructed and flagged if ambiguous
- [ ] Tables extracted with correct column alignment
- [ ] Matrices/constants extracted programmatically, not hand-transcribed
- [ ] Test vectors included for algorithm specs
- [ ] Cross-references to SDRTrunk/OP25 included where applicable
- [ ] Obsolete sections clearly marked
- [ ] Document status (active/superseded/absorbed) confirmed via web search
- [ ] File names follow the naming convention

Please deliver all files for download.


